138	<p>The settlment product currently lacks direction and tells no clear settlement story. Resulting in downstream confusion and the observed lack of adoption. This memo defines and defends the slice required to create that direction.</p>
139	
140	<h2>The slice</h2>
141	<p>Give Mariana a settlement she can trust: the deal terms she negotiates over email captured at deal creation in structured fields, and the math she walks the agent through at 2am rendered as a line-by-line statement the tour manager can trace. These two moments, deal modeling and the 2am walkthrough, are the bookends of every settlement; their mishandling is the clearest evidence of the product's missing direction. The slice aims to provide the improvements for those bookends to function as required.</p>
142	
143	<h2>Why this cut</h2>
144	<p>Deep exploration of the product and provided materials surfaced several obvious problem areas:</p>
145	
146	<ul>
147	  <li><strong>Deal modeling</strong> — only flat and %-of-gross settle in-app, vs and %-of-net (the majority of bookings) are unsupported.</li>
148	  <li><strong>Recoup terms</strong> — no structured representation, lives entirely in prose.</li>
149	  <li><strong>Expense management</strong> — distributed across accounts, manual entry, dominates Mariana's time.</li>
150	  <li><strong>Deal renegotiation</strong> — terms change after initial entry; structured fields don't allow for updates.</li>
151	  <li><strong>Recoup lifecycle</strong> — recoups have their own state (agreed/disputed/withdrawn) independent of the settlement's.</li>
152	  <li><strong>Dispute resolution</strong> — no way to handle disputed settlements in our product.</li>
153	  <li><strong>Real-time prediction</strong> — predict whether a settlement will be clean vs messy before show day.</li>
154	  <li><strong>Post-show comms</strong> — no clean way to share traceable settlement math after the show.</li>
155	  <li><strong>Lifecycle hygiene</strong> — UI status and underlying data disagree (the brief's spotting-it test).</li>
156	  <li><strong>Cap enforcement</strong> — expense and hospitality caps are set at deal time but no part of the workflow enforces them.</li>
157	</ul>
158	
159	<p>Each problem was ruled against the same question: <em>does fixing it significantly address why 82% of customers don't use the in-app tool?</em> Most fail. <strong>Expense management</strong> is the loudest transcript pain point, but the collection problem (distributed accounts) is upstream of Greenroom and spreadsheets have the same problem, a fix here doesn't move adoption. <strong>Renegotiation, recoup lifecycle, and cap enforcement</strong> are live issues and belong on the roadmap, but they're edit-time workflow and runtime enforcement gaps that build on top of structured deal entry (not implemented). <strong>Disputes, post-show comms, and lifecycle hygiene</strong> are downstream effects of unclear deal creation, which the dispute thread proved with unclear terms on how the recoup would be calculated. <strong>Real-time prediction</strong> is a new feature unrelated to core issues, therefore out of scope.</p>
160	
161	<p>Three findings from querying the database directly anchor this cut:</p>
162	<ol>
163	  <li><strong>Percentage drift</strong> — a deal's <code>dealNotesFreetext</code> describes an 85/15 net split after renegotiation, but <code>deals.percentage</code> still reads <code>0.75</code>. The engine reads the structured field, so the artist would be paid 10% less than negotiated.</li>
